Last Tsar'', London: Routledge & Kegan Paul, 1974. {{ISBN|978-0-7100-7802-5}}\n* Massie, Robert, ''Nicholas and Alexandra'', London: Pan Books, 1967. [https://archive.org/details/nicholasalexandr00mass_0 online free to borrow]\n* Massie, Robert, ''The Romanovs The Final Chapter'', New York: Ballantine Books, 1995. {{ISBN|0-345-40640-0}}\n* Tames, Richard, ''Last of the Tsars'', London: Pan Books, 1972. {{ISBN|978-0-330-02902-5}} {{OCLC|821663}}\n* Vorres, Ian, ''The Last Grand Duchess'', London: Finedawn Publishers, 1985 (3rd edition) {{OCLC|18254268}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Alexandra Fyodorovna of Hesse}}\n*[http://www.bl.uk/eblj/2006articles/article4.html \"God in All Things: The Religious Outlook of Russia's Last Empress\" by Janet Ashton]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/000327}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Hesse-Darmstadt]]|6 June|1872|17 July|1918|[[House of Hesse]]}}\n{{S-roy|ru}}\n|-\n{{S-bef|before=[[Maria Feodorovna (Dagmar of Denmark)]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Empress consort of Russia]]|years=1 November 1894 \u2013 15 March 1917}}\n{{S-non|reason=[[February Revolution|Empire abolished in 1917]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Princesses of Hesse and by Rhine}}\n{{Murder of the Romanovs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alexandra of Hesse}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Russian people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian people]]\n[[Category:19th-century Russian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:Russian saints of the Eastern Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Converts to Eastern Orthodoxy from Lutheranism]]\n[[Category:Duchesses of Holstein-Gottorp]]\n[[Category:Russian grand duchesses by marriage]]\n[[Category:German princesses]]\n[[Category:House of Hesse-Darmstadt]]\n[[Category:House of Holstein-Gottorp-Romanov]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Saint Catherine]]\n[[Category:Ladies of the Royal Order of Victoria and Albert]]\n[[Category:Russian empresses consorts]]\n[[Category:Russian-German people]]\n[[Category:Executed royalty]]\n[[Category:Executed German women]]\n[[Category:Executed Russian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by Russia]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox people executed by the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Murdered Russian royalty]]\n[[Category:Passion bearers]]\n[[Category:Victims of Red Terror in Soviet Russia]]\n[[Category:Burials at Peter and Paul Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Nicholas II of Russia]]\n[[Category:People from Darmstadt]]\n[[Category:Executed people from Hesse]]\n[[Category:Dames of the Order of Queen Maria Luisa]]\n[[Category:Dames of the Order of Saint Isabel]]\n[[Category:Christian female saints of the Late Modern era]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox royal saints]]\n", "name_user": "Smeat75", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEngagement:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandra_Feodorovna_(Alix_of_Hesse)"}
{"title_page": "Vladislav Illich-Svitych", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name=Vladislav Markovich Illich-Svitych\n|native_name=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0418\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0447-\u0421\u0432\u0438\u0442\u044b\u0447\n|image=[[File:Illich-Svitych.jpg|250px]]\n|birth_date=September 12, 1934\n|birth_place=[[Kiev]]\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1966|08|22|1934|11|12}}\n|nationality=Poland\n|occupation=Linguist\n}}\n\n'''Vladislav Markovich Illich-Svitych''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432 \u041c\u0430\u0301\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0418\u0301\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0447-\u0421\u0432\u0438\u0301\u0442\u044b\u0447}}, also transliterated as '''Illi\u010d-Svity\u010d'''; September 12, 1934 \u2013 August 22, 1966) was a linguist and [[accentology|accentologist]], also a founding father of comparative [[Nostratic]] [[linguistics]].\n\n==Biography==\nOf [[Poles|Polish]]{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}-[[Jews|Jewish]] descent, Illich-Svitych was born in [[Kiev]] but in 1941 moved with his parents to [[Orenburg|Chkalov]] and later to [[Moscow]]. His father, Mark Vladislavovich Illich-Svitych (1886\u20141963), worked as a bookkeeper; mother, Klara Moiseevna Desner (1901\u20141955) was chief director of puppet theater in Orenburg.<ref>[http://illichpv.narod.ru/biog/002.htm \u041a \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0438 \u0412. \u041c. \u0418\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0430-\u0421\u0432\u0438\u0442\u044b\u0447\u0430 (Biography of V. M. Illich-Svitych)]</ref>\n\nHe resuscitated the long-forgotten Nostratic hypothesis, originally expounded by [[Holger Pedersen (linguist)|Holger Pedersen]] in 1903, and coined the modern term ''Nostratics''. His death prevented him from completing the ''Comparative Dictionary of Nostratic Languages'', but the ambitious work was continued by his colleagues, including [[Sergei Starostin]] and [[Vladimir Dybo]].\n\nHe died in an automobile accident on August 22, 1966, near [[Moscow]].\n\n==Selected publications== \n* ''Nominal Accentuation in Baltic and Slavic'', translated by R. L. Leed and R. F. Feldstein, Cambridge, London 1979: the MIT Press. (originally edited in Russian in 1963)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Illi\u010d-Svity\u010d's law]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Merritt Ruhlen]]: ''On the Origin of Languages. Studies in Linguistic Taxonomy.'' Stanford University Press 1994.\n*Sydney M. Lamb and E. Douglas Mitchell (Hrsg.): ''Sprung from Some Common Source. Investigations into the Prehistory of Languages.'' Stanford University Press, Stanford (Calif.) 1991.\n* [[Vitaly Shevoroshkin]]: ''Reconstructing Languages and Cultures. Abstracts and Materials from the First International Interdisciplinary Symposium on Language and Prehistory.'' Brockmeyer, Bochum 1989.\n* [[Allan R. Bomhard|Bomhard, Allan R.]] and John C. Kerns: ''The Nostratic Macrofamily. A Study in Distant Linguistic Relationship''. Mouton De Gruyter. Berlin - New York 1994.\n* Dolgopolsky, Aharon: ''The Nostratic Macrofamily and Linguistic Palaeontology.'' The McDonald Institute for Archaeological Research, Oxford 1998.\n* Holger Pedersen: ''T\u00fcrkische Lautgesetze.'' ZDMG 57, 1903.\n* Holger Pedersen: ''Linguistic Science in the Nineteenth Century: Methods and Results.'' Harvard University Press, Cambridge (Mass.) 1931.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.suduva.com/virdainas/nostraticist.htm Example of Illich-Svitych's Nostratic reconstruction]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Illich-Svitych, Vladislav Markovich}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:Linguists from Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:20th-century linguists]]\n[[Category:Paleolinguists]]\n[[Category:Linguists of Nostratic languages]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name=Vladislav Markovich Illich-Svitych\n|native_name=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432 \u041c\u0430\u0301\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0418\u0301\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0447-\u0421\u0432\u0438\u0301\u0442\u044b\u0447\n|image=[[File:Illich-Svitych.jpg|270px]]\n|birth_date=September 12, 1934\n|birth_place=[[Kiev]]\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1966|08|22|1934|11|12}}\n|nationality=Poland\n|occupation=Linguist\n}}\n\n'''Vladislav Markovich Illich-Svitych''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432 \u041c\u0430\u0301\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0418\u0301\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0447-\u0421\u0432\u0438\u0301\u0442\u044b\u0447}}, also transliterated as '''Illi\u010d-Svity\u010d'''; September 12, 1934 \u2013 August 22, 1966) was a linguist and [[accentology|accentologist]], also a founding father of comparative [[Nostratic]] [[linguistics]].\n\n==Biography==\nOf [[Poles|Polish]]{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}-[[Jews|Jewish]] descent, Illich-Svitych was born in [[Kiev]] but in 1941 moved with his parents to [[Orenburg|Chkalov]] and later to [[Moscow]]. His father, Mark Vladislavovich Illich-Svitych (1886\u20141963), worked as a bookkeeper; mother, Klara Moiseevna Desner (1901\u20141955) was chief director of puppet theater in Orenburg.<ref>[http://illichpv.narod.ru/biog/002.htm \u041a \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0438 \u0412. \u041c. \u0418\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0430-\u0421\u0432\u0438\u0442\u044b\u0447\u0430 (Biography of V. M. Illich-Svitych)]</ref>\n\nHe resuscitated the long-forgotten Nostratic hypothesis, originally expounded by [[Holger Pedersen (linguist)|Holger Pedersen]] in 1903, and coined the modern term ''Nostratics''. His death prevented him from completing the ''Comparative Dictionary of Nostratic Languages'', but the ambitious work was continued by his colleagues, including [[Sergei Starostin]] and [[Vladimir Dybo]].\n\nHe died in an automobile accident on August 22, 1966, near [[Moscow]].\n\n==Selected publications== \n* ''Nominal Accentuation in Baltic and Slavic'', translated by R. L. Leed and R. F. Feldstein, Cambridge, London 1979: the MIT Press. (originally edited in Russian in 1963)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Illi\u010d-Svity\u010d's law]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Merritt Ruhlen]]: ''On the Origin of Languages. Studies in Linguistic Taxonomy.'' Stanford University Press 1994.\n*Sydney M. Lamb and E. Douglas Mitchell (Hrsg.): ''Sprung from Some Common Source. Investigations into the Prehistory of Languages.'' Stanford University Press, Stanford (Calif.) 1991.\n* [[Vitaly Shevoroshkin]]: ''Reconstructing Languages and Cultures. Abstracts and Materials from the First International Interdisciplinary Symposium on Language and Prehistory.'' Brockmeyer, Bochum 1989.\n* [[Allan R. Bomhard|Bomhard, Allan R.]] and John C. Kerns: ''The Nostratic Macrofamily. A Study in Distant Linguistic Relationship''. Mouton De Gruyter. Berlin - New York 1994.\n* Dolgopolsky, Aharon: ''The Nostratic Macrofamily and Linguistic Palaeontology.'' The McDonald Institute for Archaeological Research, Oxford 1998.\n* Holger Pedersen: ''T\u00fcrkische Lautgesetze.'' ZDMG 57, 1903.\n* Holger Pedersen: ''Linguistic Science in the Nineteenth Century: Methods and Results.'' Harvard University Press, Cambridge (Mass.) 1931.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.suduva.com/virdainas/nostraticist.htm Example of Illich-Svitych's Nostratic reconstruction]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Illich-Svitych, Vladislav Markovich}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:Linguists from Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:20th-century linguists]]\n[[Category:Paleolinguists]]\n[[Category:Linguists of Nostratic languages]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "Gnosandes", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vladislav_Illich-Svitych"}
{"title_page": "European Energy Exchange", "text_new": "{{ad|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox exchange\n|name       = EEX\n|alt_name   = European Energy Exchange AG\n|logo       = European Energy Exchange logo.svg\n|type       = Physical commodity and derivates exchange (energy)\n|city       = [[Leipzig]]\n|country    = Germany\n|coor       = {{coord|51.3379628|||N|12.3790781|||E|type:landmark}}\n|foundation = 2002\n|owner      =\n|key_people = Peter Reitz <small>([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])</small><br/>Steffen K\u00f6hler <small>([[Chief operating officer|COO]])</small><br/>Tobias Paulun <small>([[Chief strategy officer|CSO]])</small><br/>Iris Weidinger <small>([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])</small><br/>Jens Rick <small>([[Chief Information Officer|CIO]])</small><br/>\n|currency   = [[Euro|EUR]]\n|commodity  = Electric power<br/>Natural gas<br/>{{CO2}} Emission Allowances<br/>Guarantees of Origin\n|listings   =\n|mcap       =\n|volume     =\n|indexes    =\n|homepage   = {{url|www.eex.com}}\n|footnotes  =\n}}\n\n'''European Energy Exchange AG''' is a central European [[electric power]] [[List of commodities exchanges|exchange]] located in [[Leipzig]], Germany. It develops, operates and connects secure, liquid and transparent markets for energy and related products, including power derivative contracts, emission allowances, agricultural and freight products.\n\n==History==\nThe EEX emerged as a result of a [[merger]] between [[LPX Leipzig Power Exchange]] and the Frankfurt-based EEX in 2002. [[Deutsche B\u00f6rse|Deutsche B\u00f6rse Group]]\u2019s derivatives business unit [[Eurex Exchange|Eurex]] acquired the majority share in the EEX in March 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-deutscheboerse-eex-idUSTRE71M3W020110223|title=Deutsche Boerse unit buys majority in EEX|date=2017-02-23|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Ownership and subsidiaries==\nEEX AG is majority owned by Deutsche B\u00f6rse. It holds shares in the following companies:<ref>[http://www.eex.com/en/about/eex Shares held by EEX as of 2018-09-20]</ref>\n* EEX Asia, Cleartech (Cleartrade Exchange Pte Ltd.) (100%)\n* EEX CEGH Gas Exchange Services GmbH (51%)\n* EEX Link GmbH (100%)\n* enermarket GmbH (40%)\n* EPEX SPOT SE (51%)\n* European Commodity Clearing AG (100%)\n* Grexel Systems ltd (100%)\n* KB Tech Ltd. (100%)\n* Nodal Exchange Holdings, LLC (100%)\n* Power Exchange Central Europe a.s. (66,67%)\n* Spark Pte. Ltd. (25%)\n\nEEX announced that it reached agreement to acquire US-based Nodal Exchange.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.automatedtrader.net/news/at/157151/deutsche-boerses-eex-acquires-us-based-nodal-exchange|title=Deutsche Boerse's EEX acquires US based Nodal Exchange |website=www.automatedtrader.net|access-date=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Trading volume==\nIn 2018, the trading of electricity on the EEX Power Derivatives Market amounted to 3,347 TWh ([[Terawatt-hour|terawatt hours]]) compared with 2,822 in 2017. In the year 2018, a total of 577 TWh was traded on the Power Spot Markets of EPEX SPOT (2017: 543 TWh). In the field of natural gas the volume traded on the EEX amounted to 1,111 TWh, an increase of 34 percent compared with the previous year (2017: 828 TWh). The volume in trading in emission allowances amounted to 923 million tonnes in 2018 in total (previous year: 908 million tonnes.<ref>[http://www.eex.com/blob/66776/8ea17d8bc1445c4113d8774772d6dee8/pr-20140114-eex-jahresrueckblick-pdf-data.pdf EEX end-of-year-review 2013, Date: 01/14/2014]</ref>\n\n==Spot market==\nThe [[spot market]] for electricity is operated by EPEX SPOT, a joint venture owned by German EEX AG and the French Powernext SAS (its 100% daughter). On each day of the year, EPEX SPOT operates day-ahead auctions for three market areas: Germany/Austria, France and Switzerland. The physical delivery of power takes place on the next day. EPEX SPOT also provides an intraday market for Germany, France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Switzerland, Austria and the United Kingdom. This market can be used to satisfy short-term needs of electricity or to sell short-term over capacities. Participants in the market can buy up to 45 minutes before every hour electricity for the specific hour. This market operates 24/7 without exceptions. The electricity for the next day can be traded from 15:00 onwards.\n\nIn 2011, EEX introduced 24/7 trading on the Natural Gas Spot Market. On the Spot Market, companies can trade natural gas on a continuous basis for the current day (within day), one day and two days in advance as well as for the following weekend. Since the launch of 24/7 trading EEX has also offered continuous trading with a minimum lot size of 1 MW (in addition to the 10 MW contracts). Short term gas quantities can be traded on the exchange for delivery in the market areas GASPOOL, NetConnect Germany (NCG) and the Dutch Title Transfer Facility (TTF) area.\n\nEEX offers also a spot market for [[EU ETS|EU allowances]]. Since 2005, EEX operates both [[spot market|spot]] and [[derivative (finance)|derivative]]s markets in emission allowances.<ref>[http://www.eex.com/en/products/emission-allowances Emission Allowances Overview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304062035/http://www.eex.com/en/products/emission-allowances |date=4 March 2014 }}</ref> EEX has offered trading of emission allowances on the basis of the EU Emissions Trading Scheme (EU ETS) since 2005. EEX currently runs a secondary market for continuous trading on a Spot and Derivatives basis for EU ETS allowances (EUA, EUAA) and Kyoto credits (CER, ERU).<ref>[http://www.eex.com/en/products/emission-allowances/emissions-allowance-secondary-market Emission Allowances Secondary Market] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304060802/http://www.eex.com/en/products/emission-allowances/emissions-allowance-secondary-market |date=4 March 2014 }}</ref> As of March 26, 2008, it is possible to trade CER Futures on the EEX (Certified Emission Reductions), global emission credits in accordance with the Kyoto Protocol. On 14 April 2008 EEX and Eurex launched trading of options on EUA Futures. Since January 2010 EEX AG runs the auctioning of the Emission Allowances issued by the Federal Ministry of the Environment. All trading participants admitted to trading in emission allowances on EEX are able to take part in the auction without any further preconditions regarding licensing. From the very beginning, this also included all trading participants taking part in the existing Eurex cooperation on the Derivatives Market. In addition, EEX also carries out the EUA auctions for further countries (Poland, Hungary). The European Energy Exchange (EEX) has won the tendering procedure for the transitory auctioning platform for the EUA auctioned off by Germany for the third emissions trading period in February 2012 and it was chosen as cooperation exchange for the NER30 program of the European Investment Bank (EIB). As of 30 April 2012, emission allowances for the aviation industry (EU Aviation Allowances \u2013 EUAA) will also be offered for trading. Furthermore, Futures on Emission Reduction Units (ERU) will be launched at the end of April. In March, EEX extended the futures on Certified Emission Reductions (CER) for all maturities of the third trading period.\n\n==Derivatives market==\nParticipants on the EEX  can trade power contracts (weeks, months, quarters, years) up to 6 years in the future. The Power Futures are financially settled contracts, but they can be physically delivered in Germany, France, Austria, Belgium, the Netherlands and Italy (Coming). Besides electricity also natural gas futures (market areas GASPOOL and NCG), a broad range of {{CO2}} derivatives ([[Futures contract|Futures]] on EUA, CER, EUAA and ERU) can be traded at the EEX-Derivatives market.\n\n==Clearing and settlement==\nClearing and settlement of all exchange transactions is done by the European Commodity Clearing AG (ECC). ECC was founded in 2006 with the transfer of the EEX clearing activities to this subsidiary.<ref>[http://www.eex.com/en/about/newsroom/news-detail/eex-and-endex-establish-clearing-co-operation/57366 Press Release, 07/05/2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416175715/http://www.eex.com/en/about/newsroom/news-detail/eex-and-endex-establish-clearing-co-operation/57366 |date=16 April 2014 }}</ref> Specialised on the physical delivery of energy products, ECC is dedicated clearing provider for 10 exchanges: European Energy Exchange (EEX), EEX Asia, EPEX SPOT, Powernext and Power Exchange Central Europe (PXE)as well as the partner exchanges HUPX, HUDEX, NOREXECO, SEEPEX and SEMOpx. Furthermore, EEX and ECC provide the service of Trade Registration. This service enables the trading participants and the trade registration participants to conclude transactions through registration by mutual agreement or to have over-the-counter transactions registered.\n\n==Transparency==\nEEX operates \"Transparency in Energy Markets\u201d, the neutral platform for energy market data which fulfils the statutory publication requirements and implements the market participants\u2019 voluntary commitments. The platform was established by EEX and the four German transmission system operators and launched in October 2009. In 2011, the Austrian transmission system operator Austrian Power Grid AG joined the cooperation. EEX is in charge of the operation of the platform, which comprises plausibility checking, anonymisation, aggregation and publication of the data reported.\n\nOn 2 September 2014, the European Energy Exchange (EEX) launched its new transparency site. At [http://www.eex-transparency.com www.eex-transparency.com], visitors can gain access to comprehensive fundamental data and relevant information for wholesale energy trading. The website is a further development of the existing platform \u201cTransparency in Energy Market\u201d and contains information about capacity, utilization and availability of facilities for the production of electricity as well as new information on the storage of electricity and natural gas consumption.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nord Pool AS]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.eex.com/de/ Website of EEX]\n** [http://www.eex.com/en/about/newsroom/policy-newsletter Policy Newsletter of EEX]\n** [http://www.eex.com/blob/66776/8ea17d8bc1445c4113d8774772d6dee8/pr-20140114-eex-jahresrueckblick-pdf-data.pdf Annual Review 2013]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20150617220730/http://www.eex.com/blob/53944/59efc5ddff9ee4ea1fd8c9badf78bf3e/20130114-eex-jahresrueckblick-data.pdf Annual Review 2012] \n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20150617222228/http://www.eex.com/blob/52428/52fdf3ff24c627006065ae39db1543c5/20120112-eex-jahreszahlen-2011-data.pdf Annual Review 2011]\n* [http://www.eex-transparency.com/ Transparency Platform of EEX]\n* [http://www.ecc.de/ Website of ECC]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eex.com EEX website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120727141959/http://www.transparency.eex.com/en/ \"Transparency in Energy Markets\"]\n\n[[Category:Electric power exchanges in Europe]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Leipzig]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Energy in Germany]]\n[[Category:Energy in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{ad|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox exchange\n|name       = EEX\n|alt_name   = European Energy Exchange AG\n|logo       = European Energy Exchange logo.svg\n|type       = Physical commodity and derivates exchange (energy)\n|city       = [[Leipzig]]\n|country    = Germany\n|coor       = {{coord|51.3379628|||N|12.3790781|||E|type:landmark}}\n|foundation = 2002\n|owner      =\n|key_people = Peter Reitz <small>([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])</small><br/>Steffen K\u00f6hler <small>([[Chief operating officer|COO]])</small><br/>Tobias Paulun <small>([[Chief strategy officer|CSO]])</small><br/>Iris Weidinger <small>([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])</small><br/>Jens Rick <small>([[Chief Information Officer|CIO]])</small><br/>\n|currency   = [[Euro|EUR]]\n|commodity  = Electric power<br/>Natural gas<br/>{{CO2}} Emission Allowances<br/>Guarantees of Origin\n|listings   =\n|mcap       =\n|volume     =\n|indexes    =\n|homepage   = {{url|www.eex.com}}\n|footnotes  =\n}}\n\n'''European Energy Exchange AG''' is a central European [[electric power]] [[List of commodities exchanges|exchange]] located in [[Leipzig]], Germany. It develops, operates and connects secure, liquid and transparent markets for energy and related products, including power derivative contracts, emission allowances, agricultural and freight products.\n\n==History==\nThe EEX emerged as a result of a [[merger]] between [[LPX Leipzig Power Exchange]] and the Frankfurt-based EEX in 2002. [[Deutsche B\u00f6rse|Deutsche B\u00f6rse Group]]\u2019s derivatives business unit [[Eurex Exchange|Eurex]] acquired the majority share in the EEX in March 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-deutscheboerse-eex-idUSTRE71M3W020110223|title=Deutsche Boerse unit buys majority in EEX|date=2017-02-23|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Ownership and subsidiaries==\nEEX AG is majority owned by Deutsche B\u00f6rse. It holds shares in the following companies:<ref>[http://www.eex.com/en/about/eex Shares held by EEX as of 2018-09-20]</ref>\n* EEX Asia, Cleartech (Cleartrade Exchange Pte Ltd.) (100%)\n* enermarket GmbH (40%)\n* EPEX SPOT SE (51%)\n* European Commodity Clearing AG (100%)\n* Grexel Systems ltd (100%)\n* Nodal Exchange Holdings, LLC (100%)\n* Power Exchange Central Europe a.s. (66,67%)\n* Powernext SAS (100%)\n\nEEX announced that it reached agreement to acquire US-based Nodal Exchange.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.automatedtrader.net/news/at/157151/deutsche-boerses-eex-acquires-us-based-nodal-exchange|title=Deutsche Boerse's EEX acquires US based Nodal Exchange |website=www.automatedtrader.net|access-date=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Trading volume==\nIn 2018, the trading of electricity on the EEX Power Derivatives Market amounted to 3,347 TWh ([[Terawatt-hour|terawatt hours]]) compared with 2,822 in 2017. In the year 2018, a total of 577 TWh was traded on the Power Spot Markets of EPEX SPOT (2017: 543 TWh). In the field of natural gas the volume traded on the EEX amounted to 1,111 TWh, an increase of 34 percent compared with the previous year (2017: 828 TWh). The volume in trading in emission allowances amounted to 923 million tonnes in 2018 in total (previous year: 908 million tonnes.<ref>[http://www.eex.com/blob/66776/8ea17d8bc1445c4113d8774772d6dee8/pr-20140114-eex-jahresrueckblick-pdf-data.pdf EEX end-of-year-review 2013, Date: 01/14/2014]</ref>\n\n==Spot market==\nThe [[spot market]] for electricity is operated by EPEX SPOT, a joint venture owned by German EEX AG and the French Powernext SAS (its 100% daughter). On each day of the year, EPEX SPOT operates day-ahead auctions for three market areas: Germany/Austria, France and Switzerland. The physical delivery of power takes place on the next day. EPEX SPOT also provides an intraday market for Germany, France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Switzerland, Austria and the United Kingdom. This market can be used to satisfy short-term needs of electricity or to sell short-term over capacities. Participants in the market can buy up to 45 minutes before every hour electricity for the specific hour. This market operates 24/7 without exceptions. The electricity for the next day can be traded from 15:00 onwards.\n\nIn 2011, EEX introduced 24/7 trading on the Natural Gas Spot Market. On the Spot Market, companies can trade natural gas on a continuous basis for the current day (within day), one day and two days in advance as well as for the following weekend. Since the launch of 24/7 trading EEX has also offered continuous trading with a minimum lot size of 1 MW (in addition to the 10 MW contracts). Short term gas quantities can be traded on the exchange for delivery in the market areas GASPOOL, NetConnect Germany (NCG) and the Dutch Title Transfer Facility (TTF) area.\n\nEEX offers also a spot market for [[EU ETS|EU allowances]]. Since 2005, EEX operates both [[spot market|spot]] and [[derivative (finance)|derivative]]s markets in emission allowances.<ref>[http://www.eex.com/en/products/emission-allowances Emission Allowances Overview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304062035/http://www.eex.com/en/products/emission-allowances |date=4 March 2014 }}</ref> EEX has offered trading of emission allowances on the basis of the EU Emissions Trading Scheme (EU ETS) since 2005. EEX currently runs a secondary market for continuous trading on a Spot and Derivatives basis for EU ETS allowances (EUA, EUAA) and Kyoto credits (CER, ERU).<ref>[http://www.eex.com/en/products/emission-allowances/emissions-allowance-secondary-market Emission Allowances Secondary Market] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304060802/http://www.eex.com/en/products/emission-allowances/emissions-allowance-secondary-market |date=4 March 2014 }}</ref> As of March 26, 2008, it is possible to trade CER Futures on the EEX (Certified Emission Reductions), global emission credits in accordance with the Kyoto Protocol. On 14 April 2008 EEX and Eurex launched trading of options on EUA Futures. Since January 2010 EEX AG runs the auctioning of the Emission Allowances issued by the Federal Ministry of the Environment. All trading participants admitted to trading in emission allowances on EEX are able to take part in the auction without any further preconditions regarding licensing. From the very beginning, this also included all trading participants taking part in the existing Eurex cooperation on the Derivatives Market. In addition, EEX also carries out the EUA auctions for further countries (Poland, Hungary). The European Energy Exchange (EEX) has won the tendering procedure for the transitory auctioning platform for the EUA auctioned off by Germany for the third emissions trading period in February 2012 and it was chosen as cooperation exchange for the NER30 program of the European Investment Bank (EIB). As of 30 April 2012, emission allowances for the aviation industry (EU Aviation Allowances \u2013 EUAA) will also be offered for trading. Furthermore, Futures on Emission Reduction Units (ERU) will be launched at the end of April. In March, EEX extended the futures on Certified Emission Reductions (CER) for all maturities of the third trading period.\n\n==Derivatives market==\nParticipants on the EEX  can trade power contracts (weeks, months, quarters, years) up to 6 years in the future. The Power Futures are financially settled contracts, but they can be physically delivered in Germany, France, Austria, Belgium, the Netherlands and Italy (Coming). Besides electricity also natural gas futures (market areas GASPOOL and NCG), a broad range of {{CO2}} derivatives ([[Futures contract|Futures]] on EUA, CER, EUAA and ERU) can be traded at the EEX-Derivatives market.\n\n==Clearing and settlement==\nClearing and settlement of all exchange transactions is done by the European Commodity Clearing AG (ECC). ECC was founded in 2006 with the transfer of the EEX clearing activities to this subsidiary.<ref>[http://www.eex.com/en/about/newsroom/news-detail/eex-and-endex-establish-clearing-co-operation/57366 Press Release, 07/05/2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416175715/http://www.eex.com/en/about/newsroom/news-detail/eex-and-endex-establish-clearing-co-operation/57366 |date=16 April 2014 }}</ref> Specialised on the physical delivery of energy products, ECC is dedicated clearing provider for 10 exchanges: European Energy Exchange (EEX), EEX Asia, EPEX SPOT, Powernext and Power Exchange Central Europe (PXE)as well as the partner exchanges HUPX, HUDEX, NOREXECO, SEEPEX and SEMOpx. Furthermore, EEX and ECC provide the service of Trade Registration. This service enables the trading participants and the trade registration participants to conclude transactions through registration by mutual agreement or to have over-the-counter transactions registered.\n\n==Transparency==\nEEX operates \"Transparency in Energy Markets\u201d, the neutral platform for energy market data which fulfils the statutory publication requirements and implements the market participants\u2019 voluntary commitments. The platform was established by EEX and the four German transmission system operators and launched in October 2009. In 2011, the Austrian transmission system operator Austrian Power Grid AG joined the cooperation. EEX is in charge of the operation of the platform, which comprises plausibility checking, anonymisation, aggregation and publication of the data reported.\n\nOn 2 September 2014, the European Energy Exchange (EEX) launched its new transparency site. At [http://www.eex-transparency.com www.eex-transparency.com], visitors can gain access to comprehensive fundamental data and relevant information for wholesale energy trading. The website is a further development of the existing platform \u201cTransparency in Energy Market\u201d and contains information about capacity, utilization and availability of facilities for the production of electricity as well as new information on the storage of electricity and natural gas consumption.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nord Pool AS]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.eex.com/de/ Website of EEX]\n** [http://www.eex.com/en/about/newsroom/policy-newsletter Policy Newsletter of EEX]\n** [http://www.eex.com/blob/66776/8ea17d8bc1445c4113d8774772d6dee8/pr-20140114-eex-jahresrueckblick-pdf-data.pdf Annual Review 2013]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20150617220730/http://www.eex.com/blob/53944/59efc5ddff9ee4ea1fd8c9badf78bf3e/20130114-eex-jahresrueckblick-data.pdf Annual Review 2012] \n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20150617222228/http://www.eex.com/blob/52428/52fdf3ff24c627006065ae39db1543c5/20120112-eex-jahreszahlen-2011-data.pdf Annual Review 2011]\n* [http://www.eex-transparency.com/ Transparency Platform of EEX]\n* [http://www.ecc.de/ Website of ECC]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eex.com EEX website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120727141959/http://www.transparency.eex.com/en/ \"Transparency in Energy Markets\"]\n\n[[Category:Electric power exchanges in Europe]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Leipzig]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Energy in Germany]]\n[[Category:Energy in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Ursula Goetze", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Energy_Exchange"}
{"title_page": "Doc Rivers", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball coach and former player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            = Doc Rivers\n| image           = Doc Rivers.JPG\n| width           = \n| caption         = Rivers coaching the Celtics in October 2007\n| league          = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team            = Los Angeles Clippers\n| position        = [[Head coach]]\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 4\n| weight_lb       = 210\n| weight_footnote = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://stats.nba.com/player/470/|title=Doc Rivers|publisher=[[National Basketball Association]]|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1961|10|13}}\n| birth_place     = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| nationality     = American \n| high_school     = [[Proviso East High School|Proviso East]] ([[Maywood, Illinois]])\n| college         = [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]] (1980\u20131983)\n| draft_year      = 1983\n| draft_round     = 2\n| draft_pick      = 31\n| draft_team      = [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n| career_start    = 1983\n| career_end      = 1996\n| career_position = [[Point guard]]\n| career_number   = 25\n| coach_start     = 1999\n| years1          = {{nbay|1983|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1990|end}}\n| team1           = [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n| years2          = {{nbay|1991|full=y}}\n| team2           = [[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n| years3          = {{nbay|1992|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1994|start}}\n| team3           = [[New York Knicks]]\n| years4          = {{nbay|1994|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1995|end}}\n| team4           = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| cyears1         = {{nbay|1999|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2003|start}}\n| cteam1          = [[Orlando Magic]]\n| cyears2         = {{nbay|2004|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2012|end}}\n| cteam2          = [[Boston Celtics]]\n| cyears3         = {{nbay|2013|start}}\u2013present\n| cteam3          = [[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n| highlights      = \n'''As player:'''\n* [[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]] ([[1988 NBA All-Star Game|1988]])\n* [[J. Walter Kennedy Citizenship Award]] ([[1989\u201390 NBA season|1990]])\n* No. 31 [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball#Retired numbers|retired by Marquette]]\n* [[USA Basketball Male Athlete of the Year]] (1982)\n* [[Mr. Basketball USA]] (1980)\n'''As coach:'''\n* [[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[2008 NBA Finals|2008]])\n* [[NBA Coach of the Year Award|NBA Coach of the Year]] ([[1999\u20132000 NBA season|2000]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of NBA All-Star Game head coaches|NBA All-Star Game head coach]] ([[2008 NBA All-Star Game|2008]], [[2011 NBA All-Star Game|2011]])\n| stat1label    = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value    = 9,377 (10.9 ppg)\n| stat2label    = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat2value    = 4,889 (5.7 apg)\n| stat3label    = [[Steal (basketball)|Steals]]\n| stat3value    = 1,563 (1.8 spg)\n| bbr           = riverdo01\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|USA}}}}\n{{MedalSport|[[Basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[1982 FIBA World Championship|1982 Colombia]] | [[United States national basketball team|National team]]}}\n}}\n[[File:Rivers (center) sits on the sidelines with assistant coaches Tom Thibodeau (right) and Armond Hill (left) in Game 4 of the 2008 NBA Playoffs against the Atlanta Hawks.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Rivers (center) sits on the sidelines with assistant coaches [[Tom Thibodeau]] (right) and [[Armond Hill]] (left) in Game 4 of the [[2008 NBA Playoffs]] against the [[Atlanta Hawks]].]]\n[[File:Doc Champion.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Rivers at the championship parade of the [[2008 NBA Finals|2008]] [[List of NBA champions|NBA Champions]] [[Boston Celtics]].]]\n'''Glenn Anton''' \"'''Doc'''\" '''Rivers''' (born October 13, 1961) is an American [[basketball]] coach and former player who is the head coach for the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). As an NBA [[point guard]], Rivers was known for his defense, a trait that has carried over into his coaching.\n\n==Playing career==\n[[File:Doc Rivers.jpg|thumb|Rivers in 2011]]\nRivers was a [[McDonald's All-American]] for [[Proviso East High School]] in the [[Chicago metropolitan area]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-02-17/sports/ct-spt-0218-mitchell--20120218_1_austin-rivers-jabari-parker-chicago-eyes|title=Rivers reflects on stress son is under: Austin was high school phenom like his father, but Celtics coach says pressure much greater now|accessdate=February 18, 2012|date=February 18, 2012|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Mitchell, Fred}}</ref> Rivers represented the United States with the [[United States men's national basketball team|national team]] in the [[1982 FIBA World Championship]], in which he led the team to the silver medal, despite missing the last shot in the final, which could have given the title to his team. After his third season at [[Marquette University]], Rivers was drafted in the second round (31st overall<ref name=coachfile/>) of the [[1983 NBA draft]] by the [[Atlanta Hawks]]. He graduated from Marquette while completing course work as an NBA player. He spent the next seven seasons as a starter in Atlanta, assisting star [[Dominique Wilkins]] as the team found great regular-season success. He averaged a double-double for the [[1986-87 NBA season|1986\u201387 season]] with 12.8 points and 10.0 assists per game. Rivers later spent one year as a starter for the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] and two more for the [[New York Knicks]], before finishing his career as a player for the [[San Antonio Spurs]] from 1994 to 1996.\n\n==Coaching career==\n\n===Orlando Magic (1999\u20132003)===\nRivers began his coaching career with the [[Orlando Magic]] in 1999, where he coached for more than four [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] seasons. Rivers won the [[NBA Coach of the Year Award|Coach of the Year award]] in [[1999\u20132000 NBA season|2000]] after his first year with the Magic. That season, he led the team that was picked to finish last in the league to a near playoff berth.\n\nDuring the Magic's free agency spending spree in the summer of 2000, Doc Rivers had the opportunity to assemble the first \"Big Three\" team in the NBA, as the Magic were courting free agent [[Tim Duncan]], who came close to signing with the Magic and teaming up with [[Grant Hill]] and [[Tracy McGrady]]. However, Tim Duncan re-signed with the San Antonio Spurs due to Rivers' strict policy of family members not being allowed to travel in the team's plane.<ref>https://www.orlandopinstripedpost.com/2018/2/15/17018756/grant-hill-confirms-the-tim-duncan-doc-rivers-airplane-policy-story</ref>\n\nHe made the post-season in his next three years as coach, but was fired in 2003 after a 1\u201310 start to the season.\n\n===Boston Celtics (2004\u20132013)===\nAfter spending a year working as a commentator for the ''[[NBA on ABC]]'' (calling the [[2004 NBA Finals|2004 Finals]] with [[Al Michaels]]), he was hired by the [[Boston Celtics]] as their head coach in 2004. During his first years with the Celtics, he was criticized by many in the media for his coaching style, most vociferously by [[Bill Simmons]], who in 2006 publicly called for Rivers to be fired in his columns.\n\nAs a result of the Celtics' 109\u201393 victory over the [[New York Knicks]] on January 21, 2008, Rivers, as the coach of the team with the best winning percentage in the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]], earned the honor to coach the East for the [[2008 NBA All-Star Game]] in [[New Orleans Hornets|New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/news/rivers_as_080121.html|title=Doc Rivers to Coach East in 2008 All-Star Game|work=NBA.com|date=January 21, 2008|access-date=March 15, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305044857/http://www.nba.com/news/rivers_as_080121.html|archive-date=March 5, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> On June 17, 2008, Rivers won his first [[NBA Finals|NBA Championship]] as a head coach after defeating the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] in six games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2008/06/18/ring_it_up/?page=full|title=Ring it up!|date=June 18, 2008|first=Marc J.|last=Spears|newspaper=Boston Globe}}</ref> The Celtics needed an NBA record 26 post-season games to win it. Rivers played for the team that held the previous record for most games played in a single post-season: the 1994 New York Knicks played 25 post-season games.\n\nRivers led the Celtics to the [[2010 NBA Finals]] where they once again faced the Los Angeles Lakers and lost the series in seven games.\n\nAfter deliberating between staying on the job and leaving the job and returning to spend more time with his family in Orlando, Rivers finally decided that he would honor the last year of his contract and return for the 2010\u201311 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/news?slug=ys-riversceltics063010&print=1|title=Rivers returning to coach Celtics|date=June 30, 2010|first=Adrian|last=Wojnarowski|work=Yahoo! Sports}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2011, after months of rumors that he would retire, ESPN reported that the Celtics and Rivers agreed upon a 5-year contract extension worth $35 million.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/nba/news/story?id=6540602 Doc Rivers agrees to 5-year extension with Boston Celtics \u2013 ESPN Boston]. Sports.espn.go.com (May 14, 2011). Retrieved on April 20, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.nba.com/2011/news/05/13/rivers-contract-celtics.ap/index.html Rivers gets five-year extension as coach of Celtics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516122613/http://www.nba.com/2011/news/05/13/rivers-contract-celtics.ap/index.html |date=May 16, 2011 }}. NBA.com (May 13, 2011). Retrieved on April 20, 2012.</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2013, Rivers notched his 400th win with the Celtics in a 99\u201395 victory over the [[Toronto Raptors]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/games/20130206/BOSTOR/gameinfo.html \"Celtics at Raptors\"]. ''NBA.com''.</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Clippers (2013\u2013present)===\nOn June 25, 2013, the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] acquired Rivers from the Celtics for an unprotected 2015 NBA first round draft pick. He also became the senior vice president of basketball operations on the team.<ref>Patten, Eric (June 25, 2013) [http://www.nba.com/clippers/news/rivers-headed-la \"RIVERS HEADED TO L.A.\"].</ref> In his first season as their head coach, Rivers led the Clippers to a franchise-record 57 wins, garnering the 3rd seed in the Western conference. The [[2014 NBA playoffs]] first round playoff series against the [[Golden State Warriors]] was marred when TMZ released an audiotape containing racially insensitive remarks made by the then-Clippers owner [[Donald Sterling]]. Though there was a possibility of the Clippers boycotting the series, they would play on, holding a silent protest by leaving their shooting jerseys at center court and obscuring the Clippers logo on their warm-up shirts. Rivers himself stated that he would not return to the Clippers if Sterling remained as owner the following season. NBA commissioner [[Adam Silver]] responded to the controversy by banning Sterling for life and compelling him to sell the team. After the team was sold to [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Steve Ballmer]] for $2 billion on August 12, 2014, Rivers remained with the Clippers.<ref>[https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2014/4/29/5664400/doc-rivers-coach-return-donald-sterling-racism-controversy \"Doc Rivers won't return to Clippers under Donald Sterling, per report\"]. ''SBNation.com'' (Vox Media). April 29, 2014</ref>\n\nOn June 16, 2014, the Clippers promoted Rivers to president of basketball operations in conjunction with his continuing head coaching duties. Although [[Dave Wohl]] was hired as general manager, Rivers had the final say in basketball matters.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/clippers/news/clippers-restructure-basketball-operations-department \"CLIPPERS RESTRUCTURE BASKETBALL OPERATIONS DEPARTMENT\"]. ''Los Angeles Clippers''.</ref> On August 27, 2014, he signed a new five-year contract with the Clippers.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/clippers/pr-140827 \"Doc Rivers Agrees to Contract Through 2019 Season\"]. ''Los Angeles Clippers''. August 27, 2014</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2015, Rivers became the first NBA coach to coach his own son, [[Austin Rivers]] until June 26, 2018, when he was traded to the [[Washington Wizards]] for [[Marcin Gortat]].\n\nOn August 4, 2017, Rivers gave up his post as president of basketball operations. However, he continued to split responsibility for basketball matters with executive vice president of basketball operations [[Lawrence Frank]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Press Release: L.A. Clippers Announce Expansion of Leadership Team Through New Roles for Rivers, Frank|url=http://www.nba.com/clippers/press-release-la-clippers-announce-expansion-leadership-team-through-new-roles-rivers-frank|work=NBA.com|accessdate=August 4, 2017}}</ref> On May 23, 2018, Rivers and the Clippers agreed to a contract extension.<ref>{{cite web|title=L.A. Clippers, Doc Rivers, Agree to Contract Extension|url=https://www.nba.com/clippers/la-clippers-doc-rivers-agree-contract-extension|website=NBA.com|accessdate=May 23, 2018|date=May 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 31, 2019, Rivers made comments on [[Kawhi Leonard]] during an appearance on ESPN, stating that \"He is the most like Jordan that we've seen\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Youngmisuk |first1=Ohm |title=Clippers fined $50K for Rivers' Kawhi comments |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/26864879/clippers-fined-50k-rivers-kawhi-comments |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=June 5, 2019 |date=May 31, 2019}}</ref> The Clippers were fined $50,000 due to Rivers' comments in violation of the league's anti-tampering rule.<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA fines Clippers $50,000 for Rivers' comments|url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/05/31/nba-fines-la-clippers-official-release|website=NBA.com|accessdate=June 1, 2019|date=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 8, 2019, Rivers earned his 900th win as a head coach after the Clippers won against the visiting [[Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Harris|first=Beth|url=https://www.boston.com/sports/nba/2019/11/08/doc-rivers-900-wins-nba-head-coach|title=Doc Rivers earns 900th career win as Los Angeles Clippers beat Portland Trail Blazers|publisher=Boston.com|date=November 8, 2019|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1983}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1983\u201384 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta]]\n| 81 || 47 || 23.9 || .462 || .167 || .785 || 2.7 || 3.9 || 1.6 || .4 || 9.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1984}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1984\u201385 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta]]\n| 69 || 58 || 30.8 || '''.476''' || .417 || .770 || 3.1 || 5.9 || '''2.4''' || '''.8''' || 14.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1985}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1985\u201386 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta]]\n| 53 || 50 || 29.6 || .474 || .000 || .608 || 3.1 || 8.4 || 2.3 || .2 || 11.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1986}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1986\u201387 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta]]\n| '''82''' || '''82''' || 31.6 || .451 || .190 || .828 || 3.6 || '''10.0''' || 2.1 || .4 || 12.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1987}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1987\u201388 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta]]\n| 80 || 80 || 31.3 || .453 || .273 || .758 || '''4.6''' || 9.3 || 1.8 || .5 || 14.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1988}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1988\u201389 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta]]\n| 76 || 76 || 32.4 || .455 || .347 || '''.861''' || 3.8 || 6.9 || '''2.4''' || .5 || 13.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1989}}\n| style