acific||7||3||4||{{Winning percentage|3|4}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Lost in [[2017 NBA Playoffs|First Round]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2017\u201318 Los Angeles Clippers season|L.A. Clippers]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2017}}\n|82||42||40||{{Winning percentage|42|40}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2nd in Pacific||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Missed Playoffs\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018\u201319 Los Angeles Clippers season|L.A. Clippers]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2018}}\n|82||48||34||{{Winning percentage|48|34}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2nd in Pacific||6||2||4||{{Winning percentage|2|4}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Lost in [[2019 NBA Playoffs|First Round]]\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|'''Total'''\n| ||1552||894||658||{{Winning percentage|894|658}}|| ||167||84||83||{{Winning percentage|84|83}}||\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nRivers is the nephew of former NBA player [[Jim Brewer (basketball)|Jim Brewer]]. He lives in [[Orlando, Florida]],{{Update inline|?=yes|date=January 2020}} with his wife Kristen; they have four children.<ref name=coachfile>[http://www.nba.com/coachfile/doc_rivers/index.html?nav=page Doc Rivers Coaching Info] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307174222/http://www.nba.com/coachfile/doc_rivers/index.html?nav=page |date=March 7, 2009 }} at [[National Basketball Association|NBA.com]]</ref> His oldest son [[Jeremiah Rivers|Jeremiah]] played basketball at [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown University]] and [[Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball|Indiana University]],<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=3386049 Doc Rivers' son to transfer from Georgetown]. Sports.espn.go.com (May 7, 2008). Retrieved on April 20, 2012.</ref> and has played in the [[NBA D-League]] for the [[Maine Red Claws]]. His daughter Callie played [[Florida Gators women's volleyball|volleyball]] for the [[University of Florida]] <ref>[http://www.gatorsports.com/article/20071206/NEWS/71207001/1016 Rivers flows through it \u2013 News \u2013] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209070623/http://www.gatorsports.com/article/20071206/NEWS/71207001/1016 |date=December 9, 2007 }}. Gatorsports.com (December 6, 2007). Retrieved on April 20, 2012.</ref> and is married to NBA player [[Seth Curry]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dowd |first1=Katie |title=Seth Curry and Callie Rivers wed in Malibu ceremony|url=https://www.sfgate.com/warriors/article/Seth-Curry-wife-Callie-Rivers-carter-wedding-14441144.php|website=SFGate |accessdate=15 September 2019 |language=en |date=14 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lifshutz |first1=Hannah |title=Seth Curry and Doc Rivers' Daughter Are Officially Engaged |url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2019/02/seth-curry-doc-rivers-daughter-engaged |website=Complex |accessdate=17 February 2019 |language=en |date=16 February 2019}}</ref> while his younger son [[Austin Rivers|Austin]] currently plays for the [[Houston Rockets]]. His youngest son, Spencer, is a guard who played for Winter Park High School and for [[UC Irvine Anteaters men's basketball|UC Irvine]].\n \nRivers is a cousin of former [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] [[guard (basketball)|guard]] [[Byron Irvin]] and former [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] [[outfielder]] [[Ken Singleton]].<ref>[http://www.insidehoops.com/coach/doc-rivers.shtml \u2013 Doc Rivers]. Insidehoops.com. Retrieved on April 20, 2012.</ref>\n\nRivers was given his nickname of \"Doc\" by then-[[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]] assistant coach [[Rick Majerus]]. Rivers attended a summer basketball camp wearing a [[Julius Erving|\"Dr. J\"]] T-shirt. Majerus immediately called him \"Doc\" and the players at camp followed suit. The name has stuck ever since.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/coachfile/doc_rivers Doc Rivers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620041615/http://www.nba.com/coachfile/doc_rivers/ |date=June 20, 2012 }}. Nba.com. Retrieved on May 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nRivers has attention deficit hyperactivity disorder according to a personality test he took when he was coaching the Celtics.<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacMullan |first1=Jackie |title=To medicate or not? The thorny mental health issue in the NBA |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/24383926/jackie-macmullan-ocd-adhd-medication-marijuana-nba-mental-health |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=June 7, 2019 |date=August 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other work==\nRivers is also currently a member of the National Advisory Board for [[Positive Coaching Alliance]], a national non-profit organization that helps student-athletes and their coaches.<ref>[http://www.positivecoach.org/our-story/our-team/national-advisory-board/ \"National Advisory Board\"].</ref> Rivers has appeared in several videos for this organization, all of which can be found on the group's YouTube channel.<ref>{{YouTube|user=PositiveCoaching|title=Positive Coaching Alliance}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Sports}}\n*[[List of National Basketball Association career steals leaders]]\n*[[List of National Basketball Association players with most assists in a game]]\n*[[List of National Basketball Association players with most steals in a game]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Doc Rivers}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090307174222/http://www.nba.com/coachfile/doc_rivers/index.html?nav=page Doc Rivers Coaching Info] at [[National Basketball Association|NBA.com]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060308115430/http://www.databasebasketball.com/coaches/coachpage.htm?coachid=RIVERDO01 databaseBasketball.com: Doc Rivers (as coach)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060302082025/http://www.databasebasketball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=RiverDO01 databaseBasketball.com: Doc Rivers (as player)]\n\n{{Los Angeles Clippers current roster}}\n{{NBACoach}}\n{{Navboxes\n| list1 =\n{{Orlando Magic co